description: From French provingner, from provin (“a set, layer of a plant”), Old French provain, from Latin propago, propaginis, akin to propagare (“to propagate”). See propagate and prune.

verbs.description: provine (third-person singular simple present provines, present participle provining, simple past and past participle provined)

entries.meaning: (obsolete) To lay a stock or branch of a vine in the ground for propagation.
